To evaluate  
\[
\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{\sqrt{5 - h} \;-\;\sqrt{5}}{h},
\]  
multiply numerator and denominator by the conjugate of the numerator:

\[
\frac{\sqrt{5 - h} - \sqrt{5}}{h}
\;\times\;
\frac{\sqrt{5 - h} + \sqrt{5}}{\sqrt{5 - h} + \sqrt{5}}
\;=\;
\frac{(5 - h)\;-\;5}{\,h\bigl(\sqrt{5 - h} + \sqrt{5}\bigr)}
\;=\;
\frac{-\,h}{\,h\bigl(\sqrt{5 - h} + \sqrt{5}\bigr)}.
\]

Cancel the \(h\):

\[
\frac{-1}{\sqrt{5 - h} + \sqrt{5}}.
\]

Now let \(h\to0\):

\[
\lim_{h\to0}\frac{-1}{\sqrt{5 - h} + \sqrt{5}}
=\frac{-1}{\sqrt{5}+\sqrt{5}}
=\frac{-1}{2\sqrt{5}}.
\]

Answer: \(-1/(2\sqrt5)\).

To evaluate  
\[
\lim_{x\to0}\frac{x}{\sqrt{1+2x}-1},
\]  
multiply top and bottom by the conjugate of the denominator:

\[
\frac{x}{\sqrt{1+2x}-1}
\;\times\;
\frac{\sqrt{1+2x}+1}{\sqrt{1+2x}+1}
\;=\;
\frac{x\bigl(\sqrt{1+2x}+1\bigr)}{(1+2x)-1}
\;=\;
\frac{x(\sqrt{1+2x}+1)}{2x}
\;=\;
\frac{\sqrt{1+2x}+1}{2}.
\]

Now take the limit as \(x\to0\):

\[
\lim_{x\to0}\frac{\sqrt{1+2x}+1}{2}
=\frac{\sqrt{1}+1}{2}
=\frac{1+1}{2}
=1.
\]

Answer: \(1\).

The average rate of change from \(t=1\) to \(t=1.5\) is

\[
\frac{s(1.5)-s(1)}{1.5-1}
=\frac{\bigl[-64(1.5)^2+192(1.5)\bigr]\;-\;\bigl[-64(1)^2+192(1)\bigr]}{0.5}
=\frac{144-128}{0.5}
=\frac{16}{0.5}
=32
\]

So the height is increasing on average at \(32\) feet per second.
